Step 0: Update your system
sudo apt update && sudo apt upgrade -y

ğŸ”¹ Step 1: Install Java (VERY IMPORTANT)

Jenkins requires Java. Use Java 17 (recommended).

sudo apt install -y openjdk-17-jdk


Verify:

java -version


âœ” You should see openjdk 17

ğŸ”¹ Step 2: Add Jenkins Official Repository (SAFE WAY)
2.1 Add Jenkins key
curl -fsSL https://pkg.jenkins.io/debian-stable/jenkins.io-2023.key | sudo tee \
/usr/share/keyrings/jenkins-keyring.asc > /dev/null

2.2 Add Jenkins repo
echo deb [signed-by=/usr/share/keyrings/jenkins-keyring.asc] \
https://pkg.jenkins.io/debian-stable binary/ | sudo tee \
/etc/apt/sources.list.d/jenkins.list > /dev/null

ğŸ”¹ Step 3: Install Jenkins
sudo apt update
sudo apt install -y jenkins


âœ” No errors should appear here.

ğŸ”¹ Step 4: Start & Enable Jenkins
sudo systemctl start jenkins
sudo systemctl enable jenkins


Check status:

sudo systemctl status jenkins


âœ” You should see active (running)

ğŸ”¹ Step 5: Allow Jenkins Port (8080)
sudo ufw allow 8080

ğŸ”¹ Step 6: Open Jenkins in Browser

Open browser and go to:

http://localhost:8080


(or VM IP: http://<vm-ip>:8080)

ğŸ”¹ Step 7: Get Jenkins Admin Password

In terminal:

sudo cat /var/lib/jenkins/secrets/initialAdminPassword


Copy the password â†’ paste in browser.

ğŸ”¹ Step 8: Finish Setup

Click Install Suggested Plugins

Create Admin User

